<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by John Midgley BSc (hons)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">              </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by John Midgley (CCS16)</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:10pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:14pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This document discusses the social, policy and scientific barriers to industrial scale implementation of Carbon Storage (CCS) in the UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and UK continental shelf.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The author is a professional </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">geoscientist with 25 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">years of practical </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">oil and gas well design, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">construction </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and monitoring </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">experience with energy companies and environmental partners.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The author </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">was a senior manager on a CCS </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">project in North Africa between 2008 and 2012, seeing the project through to completion with responsibility for fieldwork, environmental monitoring and liaison with public bodies.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Economic barriers to successful implantation of CCS are discussed, concludin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">g that costs will be high due to the duration of the project with respect to long-term monitoring.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Political considerations conclude that CCS will only succeed under a robust and multi-administration aegis that can weather short-term public disapproval.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">gulation will struggle taking into account existing environmental law and general environmental law may also need revision. This has the advantage of also allowing modernization and updating to take into account nuclear waste, fracking and public opinion.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Science obstacles to CCS, while existing, can be mitigated by improved multi-disciplinary funding.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Social barriers are the main barriers to industrial scale implementation of onshore (near to source) CCS. These can be mitigated with time, education and lin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">king of limitations to benefits for the consumer.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The conclusion that CCS is a positive action in the UK that will pay dividends in climate change mitigation, promote the UK knowledge economy and help influence developing countries in accepting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cost-effect</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ive carbon friendly energy generation.</span></li></ul><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:10pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:10pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:10pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:14pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Statement of competency</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">My comments below are based on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">experience gained</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as Fieldwork and Operations Coordinator (2008 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">– </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2013) on the BP, Statoil and Sonatrach joint venture In Salah Gas CCS project. My academic and research qualifications are based on BSc. Hons Combined Science (Geology), MSc. Earth &amp; Environmental Science, M</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Sc. Science &amp; Society, BA Hons (Open) focussed on environmental policy and a soon to be completed MA in education focussed on societal and adult learning. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">I am a fellow of the Geological Society of London (F.G.S.) and a member of the Energy Institute (E.I.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">). Currently I am an independent consult on CCS, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Alternative Energy, S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hale</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Gas (f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">racking</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and public acceptance issues relating to science and technology. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">My primary research </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">interests are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> scientific</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, regulatory</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and social aspects of long-term environmental monitoring and inter-generational equity and sustainability. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">I was part of the team who conducted technical appraisals for the UK Government CCS Commercialisation Competition in 2013.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The following</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> comments </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are brief with respect to agreements on confidentiality made to clients (BP Alternative Energy and Senergy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) and research not yet completed.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The comments in this document are the basis for a PhD research proposal under discussion for funding.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:14pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Evidence for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">the Commons Select Committee on Carbon Capture and Storage</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">1)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">What are the main barriers (e.g. economic, political, regulatory, scientific and social) to developing large-scale integrated CCS projects in the UK and internationally? How can they be overcome?</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There are considerable barriers to successful implementation of CCS in the UK. Over the last few decades, public expectations of benefits from the environment in which they live have grown immeasurably, in part this is due to a better personal understandi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ng of the physical environment and the part it plays in their lives but is also in part to the increased cultural significance for leisure, social acceptance and its value as inter-generation equity. In parallel to this there has now an automatic and uninf</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ormed deep cultural shift of enmity toward groups who wish to manipulate this environment for gain. This is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">expressed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in emotional and uninformed stances to nuclear power, fracking, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and potentially CCS. So far, CC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">S has not become a focus for anti-science s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">entiment but given the shared history and mechanisms it has with both deep nuclear waste storage and shale gas fracking there is great potential for public mistrust in carbon storage.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Political barriers potentially fall into two groups </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">–</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The lack of long-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">term policy commitment to cost and infrastructure demands. A very expensive leader project started by one administration could easily become a target for cuts by another.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Tyranny of the weak</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">” – </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uninformed voters opposed to CCS could produce a power bl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ock that unseats local councillors and MP</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s, therefore dictating otherwise beneficial policy.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> This has happened with respect to nuclear waste facilities and will probably happen in response to fracking.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Regulatory barriers are considerable and at present </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">not clearly defined. There are pre-existing international and national law on atmospheric emissions, maritime and ground water pollution but they do not directly address CO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> emissions into the biosphere or geosphere. The legal definition of waste pertainin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">g to CO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is not clear and open to a wide range of interpretations. Ideally CCS legislation will have to be congruent with the existing body of environmental law (some is 200 years old) as well as addressing inter-generational commitments for monitoring, da</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mages and decommissioning payments. The legislative body evolving a legislative framework should comprise scientists, environmentalists and legal persons.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Scientific barriers can and will be mitigated and/or managed by adequate funding and appropriate regu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">latory frameworks. The question is how much and how intrusive?</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Social barriers are the most threatening to CCS projects. Without public backing the government will be called upon to act in a manner that may not be conducive to full and economic applicatio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n of these technologies. Science and society live in a shared environment (literally), however that society is deficit in both scientific knowledge and long-term vision and is becoming increasingly vocal in expressing itself at corporate targets. Without p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">roper placement of these technologies in the public psyche CCS may attract the same ire as fracking and nuclear waste (indeed legislation, monitoring and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">infrastructure is very similar between all three). Potential solutions for this include but are not li</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mited to</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Formalising sustainability as a subject in the national curriculum using in part, visiting experts outside the traditional teaching hierarchy.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Undertaking a government media strategy placing sustainability topics such as CCS in the public arena </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(ref. the MAFF approach with The Archers (Godfrey Baseley, BBC 1950)).</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Incentives for communities willing to host CCS (and fracking / nuclear waste) infrastructure. These incentives should not be direct payment of monies but rather enhanced amenities. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Lower council tax sends the wrong message although a deal on cost of energy bills from suppliers and not directly from government would help.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">2)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Are there any safety issues associated with capturing, transporting and storing carbon dioxide? How could they be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> overcome? Who should have responsibility for ensuring these activities are safe?</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The potential risks associated with deep geologic storage of CO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> are well known and the focus of many research projects. In my experience gained with the In Salah Gas CO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> storage project (</span><a href="http://www.insalahco2.com/"><span style="color:#0563c1; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.insalahco2.com/</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) there are significant obstacles in data acquisition </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">translating</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the results of these projects to an industrial scale.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Data acquisition is costly and intrusive. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Good characterization of a potential site is not limited to geomechanical and fluid flow / poro-perm properties. Hydrogeological studies, soil mapping and ecological surveys must also be undertaken to a level of monitoring that goes beyond current Environm</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ental Impact Assessment (EIA) standards due to the subtleties of CO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> impact and that CO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is naturally occurring in the geosphere and biosphere requiring isotopic differentiation. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The cost of specialised probes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and surveys </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for soil gas and water quality mon</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">itoring is high</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (millions of dollars)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Installation by competent persons is required and regular maintenance is mandatory to ensure quality data. Data collection is also costly either in CAPEX for high-end equipment or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">OPEX in manpower and time over the li</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">fe of the project for manual collection. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We had very good results from InSAR (satellite based ground movement observations) albeit </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ground truthing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">verification was difficult and costly. While this originally made a very good communication tool correct in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">terpretations of nuanced data requires highly trained and experienced persons. These specialist skills are lacking in a general workforce so the work will tend to focus a few people and companies rather than a publically accountable body.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There is also th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e question of timescale for monitoring, based on work in Algeria on the Cretaceous aquifer I estimated a minimum monitoring programme of seventy (70) years</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as a minimum</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Long-term monitoring to enable a statistically significant level of proper (as in publ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ic interest) decision making makes monitoring an inter-generational project.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> This is a major social rather than scientific barrier and will attenuate investment and incubation of the field depending on how the risks are framed by regulation and government </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">policy.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Concomitant to this are issues around handover and responsibility as the potential risks will outlive the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">normal</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lifespan of a commercial concern. Depending on the site, pollution transport associated with CCS activities can be a very slow proces</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s (e.g. movement of heavy minerals, CO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> polluted water, arsenic related to corrosion etc.)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> so it is possible that plumes of pollution may n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ot be identified for many years and only become apparent when the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">polluter</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is no longer in business. This invalidat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">es the current </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">polluter pays</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">model for environmental pollution control.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">3)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Could the successful development of CCS improve international efforts to mitigate climate change? What role could UK CCS play in this?</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Yes. The work of Socolow et al. </span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">wedges</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, shows the potential for CCS to impact on climate change. The question that needs clarification is at what cost and are other equally as effective alternatives cheaper? In my opinion there are, but they require the mobilization to action of so</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cieties </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to make small personal changes. If each of the 7 billion people on the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">planet make a single carbon negative action it will have a great impact. Unfortunately, enabling this </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is very difficult in a consumerist </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and highly politicized </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">society. Where CC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">S has an advantage</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is that action, taken by a relative few, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">will</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> have a global impact.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">For incubating CCS, the leadership of the UK in this field, and the UK reputation for scientific excellence will enhance our quaternary knowledge economy. UK CCS leade</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rship will create confidence, that confidence, will sway other countries, particularly non-OECD countries with emerging fossil fuel based economies to practice CCS.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> There are also spin off technologies from CCS that will be applicable to both nuclear waste</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and shale gas fracking industries to make them safer, more cost effective and potentially more consumer friendly.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Endnote</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">My comments bridge both science research, public acceptance and environmental policy. Please let me know if you would like to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">discuss these issues further.</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">http://www.globalccsinstitute.com/insights/authors/adamaston/2011/10/17/wedges-reaffirmed-robert-socolow-updates-his-wedges-ana</span></p></body></html>